description:
Acacia longifolia (Andrews) Willd. Part of the family Fabaceae, sub family Mimosaceae, as identified by the seed pods produced in this specimen. 
A coastal shrub, the ‚Äòleaves‚Äô are modified phyllodes which is a characteristic of the genus Acacia. These phyllode leaves are thin and flexible with 2 main veins. The leaves are tough, smooth and are matte in texture. The Acacia genus has a particular of inflorescence whereby flowers are petite, often golden yellow, consisting of multitudes of stamens and flowers are distinctly clustered (in this case into a cylinder). There are two subspecies of the Acacia longifolia, this is most likely Acacia longifolia var.sophorae, as it was growing in sandy soils, was a low sprawling shrub, and has blunt and broader phyllode leaves, whereas Acacia longifolia var. longifolia is a taller shrub, in damper areas with longer, narrower phyllode leaves (as described in Les Robinsons field guide to the native plants of Sydney).

Mimosa (Albizia julibrissin)

26 June 2016 
Lyndon B. Johnson National Grassland 
County Road 2560 & Forest Service Road 900 
Wise County, Texas

A single Mimosa tree that had been heavily pruned at some point was making a comeback and its canopy was ablaze in its bright pink and white flowers. From Pennsylvania and Massachusetts on the East Coast of the United States to California on the West Coast, Mimosa makes its presence known as an introduced species. It is not found in Canada, even as an introduced species according to the range map of the Plants Database. But though not indicated it is certainly found in Mexico and perhaps farther south in the Americas. Additional common names for this tree include Persian Silk Tree and Pink Silk Tree. It is a tree that's native to "southwestern and eastern Asia," according to its Wikipedia entry. The Lyndon B. Johnson National Grassland is administered by the US Forest Service, US Department of Agriculture.
